<br>
Other cultures in the world view marriage as a man and his female property or properties. There was even one culture where it was a woman and her male properties. <br>
<br>
Monogamous lifelong commitment exists was not even the norm for relationships in most pre-christian cultures.<br>
<br>
Celtic marriages were renewed annually with the option not to renew. Roman and greek marriages were frequently not a sexual commitment so much as a social/economic commitment. <br>
<br>
In most cultures sex between people of the same gender was not even considered sex because it couldnt produce offspring. It was not even considered taboo in most cultures until the christian age.<br>
<br>
One on one marriage in terms of human history has been a fairly recent development. Even in christian history there have been cases of multiple marriages sanctioned by the christian church. Though most modern translations of the new testament forbid polygamy, early greek translations did not. The words were changed in early translations and stuck.<br>
<br>
The old testament certainly did not forbid polygamy, though it is not practiced in the modern jewish religion mostly due to the fact that most jewish people live under laws developed for christian morals.<br>
<br>
The concept of sexual relationships outside or in addition to marriage being a sin is not unique to christianity but is not so great a transgression as it is in christianity. I think Islam may be more strict on the subject but most other religions that even have rules concerning it do not consider it an irreparable transgression.<br>
<br>
Marriage in most cultures prior to modern times was an economic arrangement more than a personal commitment. And in any economic relationship, love and pleasure may be sought elsewhere. No one usually had problems with this.<br>
<br>
The odus on polygamy and open marriage will probably remain as long as the christian/islamic religions, but, luckily, we live in a time when the last thousand years of prudism are ending. People are becoming more aware intellectually and spiritually. We are beginning to understand that its not all about sexual property. One or two thousand years is not a long time in human history. Four thousand years from now people will probably be shocked at the level of control that people placed on their spouses today, just as we are shocked when we hear about how women were property in centuries past.<br>
<br>
I currently live in a monogamous relationship by choice, not because some one told me I had to. Before we had children Evelle and I frequently shared our bed with other women, heck we even had a girl stay with us on our honeymoon. Our choice to stop having extramarital was for the sake of our children not because we think it is morally wrong, but because we know others teach their children that it is and we don't want our children stigmitized because of mommy and daddy's girlfriends.<br>
<br>
Modern culture is become less controlled and that is a good thing. Now if we could all just learn to respect each others ability to make our own choices we would all be better off.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
